<article class="essay" id="main">

  <header class="essay-head">
    <p class="essay-kicker">Goodneighbor &middot; a design practice</p>
    <h1 class="essay-h1">Consulting</h1>
    <p class="essay-lede">I help when too many true things are competing for the same decision.</p>
  </header>

  <section class="essay-opener" id="opener">
    <p>In wood, a knot is where a branch met the trunk. The grain bends around it and takes on a different character &ndash; sometimes weaker, harder to cut (but sometimes more beautiful). If you try to handplane it like &ldquo;clear grain,&rdquo; the surface tears. If you build across it without reading it, the joinery fails.</p>

    <p>Common wisdom says avoid knots. Buy the clearest, tightest, straightest grain you can find. In the real world, there is no clear grain. It&rsquo;s mostly knots.</p>

    <p>Complex work is like this. A knot is a design problem where history, capacity, and constraint are all in play at once. I&rsquo;m good with knots.</p>

    <p>You read the wood. You decide whether to cut it out, stabilize it, work around it, or let it become the feature. My job is to read the grain with you, name the knots as I see them, and help you decide. I can also help with the carpentry, once we know what we&rsquo;re working with.</p>

    {# PLACEHOLDER connective line — voice-gate #}
    <p class="essay-note">For people and teams trying to move ideas through institutions. The work groups three ways: <strong>Sense</strong> (get a true read), <strong>Design</strong> (shape where decisions get made), and <strong>Build</strong> (make the capability stick).</p>
  </section>

  {# ============ SENSE ============ #}
  <section class="knot-group" id="sense">
    <h2 class="knot-group-head">Sense <span class="knot-group-sub">&ndash; get a true read of the work</span></h2>

    <article class="knot" id="evidence">
      <p class="knot-label">EVIDENCE</p>
      <p class="knot-tag">the literature won&rsquo;t make the call</p>
      <p>The research is real. The data is partial. Experts disagree by implication. The evidence answers a nearby question instead of yours. People in the room are using the word &ldquo;evidence&rdquo; to mean different things.</p>
      <p>This is the gap between knowing more and deciding better. Most evidence-based work stalls here. Once the synthesis is done, somebody still has to choose.</p>
      <p>A common failure mode is using &ldquo;we need more evidence&rdquo; as a deferral mechanism rather than a real research need. Sometimes that&rsquo;s right. Often it&rsquo;s avoidance.</p>
      <p class="knot-do"><span class="knot-do-label">What I do:</span> separate what&rsquo;s known, assumed, contested, missing, and usable. Write a decision frame the evidence can inform. Track the open questions so they don&rsquo;t get lost between meetings.</p>
      <p class="knot-artifacts"><span class="knot-artifacts-label">Artifacts:</span> evidence brief, assumptions ledger, decision frame, open-questions list.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="knot" id="field-reality">
      <p class="knot-label">FIELD REALITY</p>
      <p class="knot-tag">the dashboard is smoother than the work</p>
      <p>The strategy reads tight. Coverage is green. At the household visit, the supervisor&rsquo;s morning meeting, or the handoff between teams, something else is going on.</p>
      <p>This is usually a labor and information problem. Somebody is improvising to keep things running and not telling anyone upward. Something is being routed around. Local knowledge is holding a joint together that the plan never named. Refusal is showing up as low coverage and getting coded as a logistics issue.</p>
      <ul class="knot-tells">
        <li>&ldquo;coverage&rdquo; is the only metric anyone trusts</li>
        <li>supervisors know things that don&rsquo;t make it into reports</li>
        <li>the same workaround shows up at three sites and surprises everyone</li>
        <li>the team has stopped sharing the things they think will get them in trouble</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="knot-do"><span class="knot-do-label">What I do:</span> figure out what&rsquo;s actually happening at the level of work, what people aren&rsquo;t saying upward, and what the strategy needs to absorb to stay honest. Build something to keep that information flowing, not just for one round.</p>
      <p class="knot-artifacts"><span class="knot-artifacts-label">Artifacts:</span> field readout, friction map, working notes, feedback loop design.</p>
    </article>
  </section>

  {# ============ DESIGN ============ #}
  <section class="knot-group" id="design">
    <h2 class="knot-group-head">Design <span class="knot-group-sub">&ndash; shape where decisions get made</span></h2>

    <article class="knot" id="priorities">
      <p class="knot-label">PRIORITIES</p>
      <p class="knot-tag">too many &ldquo;right&rdquo; answers, no clear solution</p>
      <p>You have more legitimate priorities than capacity to work on. Every one has a sponsor and a defensible case. The ranking exercise keeps producing a list nobody believes, including the people who made it.</p>
      <p>This is usually a decision-class problem. The room is running a prioritization process when the actual question is portfolio shape, or sequencing, or what kind of bet you&rsquo;re making. Different questions need different tools. Most teams reach for the prioritization rubric by default.</p>
      <ul class="knot-tells">
        <li>&ldquo;and&rdquo; is doing the work &ldquo;or&rdquo; should be doing</li>
        <li>the loudest voice and the most senior voice keep producing different rankings</li>
        <li>the strategy doc has more line items than last quarter, not fewer</li>
        <li>somebody says &ldquo;we should be able to do all of this&rdquo;</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="knot-do"><span class="knot-do-label">What I do:</span> figure out what kind of decision it actually is, name the binding constraint (attention, calendar, political capital, money), get clear on who owns the cut, and work through it.</p>
      <p class="knot-artifacts"><span class="knot-artifacts-label">Artifacts:</span> priority map, decision criteria, cut list with rationale, sequencing memo. Sometimes a meeting design if the room needs to ratify the cuts together.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="knot" id="public-concern">
      <p class="knot-label">PUBLIC CONCERN</p>
      <p class="knot-tag">when &ldquo;messaging&rdquo; is the wrong frame</p>
      <p>A campaign, technology, or research agenda has social friction that communications work cannot resolve. Trust, consent, refusal, governance, and institutional memory are inside the technical work whether the plan says so or not.</p>
      <p>I&rsquo;ve spent time here in gene drives, mass drug administration, disease-control campaigns, and intimate partner violence research. The pattern is consistent. The concern is rarely about the technology in isolation. It&rsquo;s about whose authority decides, whose body bears the risk, who got asked, who didn&rsquo;t, and whether the last round was handled well.</p>
      <p class="knot-do"><span class="knot-do-label">What I do:</span> surface the concerns in time to shape design. Map where institutional responsibility sits. Help design engagement that gets used in decisions, not stored in an appendix.</p>
      <p class="knot-artifacts"><span class="knot-artifacts-label">Artifacts:</span> concern map, engagement frame, governance brief, language audit.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="knot" id="translation">
      <p class="knot-label">TRANSLATION</p>
      <p class="knot-tag">same words, different things</p>
      <p>Researchers, operators, funders, designers, community partners, institutions &ndash; all in the room. The memo says you all agree. You don&rsquo;t.</p>
      <p>It&rsquo;s rarely personality. It&rsquo;s mismatched standards of proof, timelines, incentives, and definitions of success. The disagreement gets papered over and the work splits at the first joint that needs more than nodding.</p>
      <ul class="knot-tells">
        <li>everyone agrees in the meeting and the follow-up emails describe different next steps</li>
        <li>&ldquo;we&rdquo; is doing too much work in the strategy doc</li>
        <li>one group&rsquo;s &ldquo;evidence&rdquo; is another group&rsquo;s &ldquo;anecdote&rdquo;</li>
        <li>the team that was supposed to inherit the work is rebuilding it from scratch</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="knot-do"><span class="knot-do-label">What I do:</span> get the disagreement on the table early, where it can be worked. The form depends on what&rsquo;s misaligned &ndash; sometimes a glossary, sometimes a role map, sometimes a workshop structured around the actual fault line.</p>
      <p class="knot-artifacts"><span class="knot-artifacts-label">Artifacts:</span> glossary, role map, shared frame, decision memo, workshop design.</p>
    </article>
  </section>

  {# ============ BUILD ============ #}
  <section class="knot-group" id="build">
    <h2 class="knot-group-head">Build <span class="knot-group-sub">&ndash; make the capability stick</span></h2>

    <article class="knot" id="tools">
      <p class="knot-label">TOOLS</p>
      <p class="knot-tag">when the form flattens the work</p>
      <p>A rubric, prompt, runbook, dashboard, or template was supposed to help people think. It&rsquo;s flattening the work instead. The form doesn&rsquo;t understand the material it&rsquo;s being applied to.</p>
      <p>This is usually a tacit-knowledge transfer problem. The people who could build the right tool are too busy doing the work to notice the tool is wrong, and the people building the tool aren&rsquo;t doing the work.</p>
      <p class="knot-do"><span class="knot-do-label">What I do:</span> turn tacit expertise into tools that hold context, with use notes that flag where the tool stops working.</p>
      <p class="knot-artifacts"><span class="knot-artifacts-label">Artifacts:</span> runbook, checklist, rubric, prompt set, small prototype.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="knot knot--placeholder" id="training">
      <p class="knot-label">TRAINING &amp; CAPACITY</p>
      <p class="knot-tag">building skill that outlasts the engagement</p>
      {# PLACEHOLDER — voice-gate. This is the surface the Emory Centers / Lynel Blaze /
         Karen capacity-building opportunity needs to see. Lee to write in his voice,
         positioned AGAINST hollow "training cascade" workshops per the essay. #}
      <p>[PLACEHOLDER &ndash; Lee&rsquo;s voice] Turn hard-won expertise into training and capacity-building that holds up in the field &ndash; designed so it arrives with the tools, time, and authority to actually use it, and an honest map of where it stops working. Capacity-building for teams, programs, and organizations.</p>
      <p class="knot-do"><span class="knot-do-label">What I do:</span> [PLACEHOLDER] design and run training and capacity-building that transfers judgment, not just procedure.</p>
      <p class="knot-artifacts"><span class="knot-artifacts-label">Artifacts:</span> [PLACEHOLDER] curriculum, facilitation design, field guides, train-the-trainer materials.</p>
    </article>
  </section>

